"{\"uid\": \"myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com-news-judo-olympics-solidarity-course-completed\", \"text\": \"Subscribe Now  KATHMANDU, Feb 26:\\u00a0The International Olympics Solidarity Course organized by the Nepal Judo Association (NJA) has been completed on Sunday.  The course, which was started with support from the Nepal Olympic Committee (NOC) and the International Olympic Committee (IOC), was attended by 40 trainees. \\u00a0It aimed at refreshing the skills of judo coaches of Nepal. The association said that such a program was crucial to produce new judo players and help grow Nepali judo industry.  Noted expert from the International Judo Federation (IJF) Amar Merigja was the main trainer of the course. Suprasiddha Tamrakar and Rajeev Pradhan were the co-trainers.  On the same occasion, the NJA also organized an orientation for 20 referees on the management of judo. NJA general secretary Dharma Shrestha, main coach Birendra Ranjit, and international referee Manoj Bahadur KC served as resource persons to train the referees on the new regulations of judo that were introduced this year.  The National Sports Council (NSC)'s vice-president Lama Tendi Sherpa handed over certificates to the trainees at the end of the course on Sunday.  Lama said that the training would be helpful in the promotion of judo in Nepal, adding that the Nepali sports sector had a lot of hope from judo. Expressing his confidence on the judokas, he said that they had the potential to bring medals in the Olympics after the training seminar.    Ballot Box Revolt: What RSP's breakthrough victory...  Warning, Threat or Opportunity? Nepal's major part...  Granary in crisis: Water politics leave Madhesh pa...  \\\"China stands ready to work with Nepal to carry forward the traditional friendship, deepen practical cooperation and advance bilateral relations\\\", read the statement.  Building Nepal's Digital Future  Fuel shortages in Nepal: A hidden threat to health a...  Second Innings of Balen and Gagan  Who will become Balen's climate pilot?  Three \\\"S\\\" factors-sulabhata (availability), sangat (peer influence), and siko (imitation)-are driving Madhesh's youth toward drug addiction.<...  Three \\\"S\\\" factors-sulabhata (availability), sangat (peer influence), and siko (imitation)-are driving Madhesh's youth toward drug addiction.<...  ANFA CEO Indraman Tuladhar said the ANFA submitted all necessary documents regarding foreign players' visas to the Ministry of Youth and Sports and the National Sports Council one and a half mon...  Nepal Republic Media Limited \\u00a9 2026.All right reserved  Nepal Republic Media Limited \\u00a9 2024. All right reserved |Privacy Policy|Terms of use  Gain access to up to 10 free articles per month.  Already have an account?Log                         in\"}"